Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He especially hated it because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his platoon. Quietly, he got up from his cot, put on his combat suit, threw his body armor over it, and took his belongings out of the locker, being particularly careful with a certain small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed hung from there, like his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, mud and ice creaked under his boots.
He pulled a lighter from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short drag before opening the door a little. In the last week, he had to come up with quite a few ideas to wake the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, because it usually didn't work and only produced a faint sound from the speakers.
"Will you wake her?" Cohren turned around and saw conductor Nemic approaching him.
"Yes," answered Cohren.
"What are you going to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came towards him already in full gear.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What did you wake up from?" asked Cohren.
"So, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting for whatever new idea you've come up with today. And secondly, the shock troops, who get up first, get to choose the morning ration," replied one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, corporal," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm echoed through the barracks. Inside, he heard muffled swearing and people running about in confusion.
"Hey, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
“Well, my people from the training camp have learned it,” replied Cohren, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. “However, the platoon and company commanders also know that they have to stand up before their units.”
A few seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, others more annoyed.
"Good morning," said Cohren in a good mood.
"Respectfully, sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?" asked a sergeant from the assault troops.
"Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn't oversleep," said Cohren.
"Pack up all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for supervising and supporting them together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We are not coming back here. Corporals and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for final checks and to pack your daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They had been part of the second assault division, second army. Before they were combined, they had been two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company had been split, and that was the main reason why Cohren felt mixed emotions about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operating base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid detection by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel attacks from the air and on the ground to combat them.
"Another day and a new task for the Hellhounds," said Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward operating base outside of Ianlos. We'll support the ground attack," answered Cohren, pulling on his cigarette. He partially blamed Craith for getting him started on smoking, but a year in the field changed a person, so he said nothing.
"Shit. It's getting worse at the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news says: 'Support the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' How about some help for the Howland front instead?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren, flicking the remains of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're starting off with the first armed train and won't have to run. Hauptmann Shaw should already be there."
"Did Shaw make it clear that he's giving us a ride?" Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
"Ja. He's actually not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but you can get along with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and put on his backpack. "All units of the Exodus Company will gather at West Yard when they're done. We'll depart with the first armed train at 0500."
Within seconds, he received a reply from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik had been low-ranking corporals when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren had the feeling that he had known them for ages, even though it had been at most two years. They were squad leaders, although Craith had been commanding the second platoon for a week, after its previous leader had been discharged for medical reasons following a shooting by a Daybreak sniper.
On their way to the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic spotted a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four armored troop carriers. Their crews were moving around, ensuring that their machines were combat-ready. Quickly, Cohren recognized Hauptmann Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armed patrol. As they approached, Shaw looked over to them and walked toward them, as always with an expressionless face.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said, noting that Cohren was slower, as he looked at Cohren's pistol holster and then looked up again. "The company is ready, I assume?"
